Part I - San Francisco Bay Ford GoBike Service¶

by Excellent Ikeakanam¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. This dataset includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.The Ford GoBike services is a bike sharing transportation provided by Ford that is easy to use, enjoyable and convenient. There are several bike stations, both start stations and end stations. People use bike sharing for many different reasons, such as commuting to work or school, running errands, and getting to and from appointments.The dataset contains the February 2019 records which has 183,412 records and 16 features. The dataset contains details of stations, duration of rides, gender, and types of users. The service has two types of users which are Customers and Subscribers. I am going to be carrying out exploratory and explanatory data analysis on the dataset.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 183412 rows and 16 columns.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of my interest in this dataset are

  • user types
  • member gender
  • member age
  • start_weekdays and period of day

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The features that would help me support my investigation into the features of my interest are start_station_name, usertype, start_time, member_birth_year, member_gender, duration, period_of_Day

Observations from the dataset¶

I observed some quality and tidiness issues in the dataset which are going to be addressed before the exploratory analysis. Some of these issues include:

  • Convert datatypes like the time variables, which are the start_time and end_time variables should be converted to datetime datatype instead of string datatype, the user_type, member_gender and bike_share_for_all_trip variables can be converted to categorical variables, bike_id can be converted to string datatype
  • The start_time variable could be broken down further into hour of the day, day of the week, month of the year.
  • Derive the age of the members from their birth year information

Cleaning the dataset¶

ford_clean = ford_df.copy()
In [11]:
#convert datatypes to correct datatypes

#start_time and end_time variables to datetime datatype
ford_clean['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(ford_clean['start_time'])
ford_clean['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(ford_clean['end_time'])

#user_type, member_gender, and bike_share_for_all_trip variables to categorical datatype
for col in ['member_gender', 'user_type', 'bike_share_for_all_trip']:
    ford_clean[col] = ford_clean[col].astype('category')
    
#bike_id variable to string datatype
ford_clean['bike_id'] = ford_clean['bike_id'].astype('object')

#split the time variables into hour, day of the week, month of the year
#month of the year
ford_clean['start_month_num'] = ford_clean['start_time'].apply(lambda time: time.month)
ford_clean['start_month_name'] = ford_clean['start_month_num'].apply(lambda x: calendar.month_abbr[x])

#hour of the day
ford_clean['start_hour'] = ford_clean['start_time'].apply(lambda time: time.hour)
ford_clean['period_of_day'] = 'morning'
ford_clean['period_of_day'][(ford_clean['start_hour'] >= 12) & (ford_clean['start_hour'] <= 17)] = 'afternoon'
ford_clean['period_of_day'][(ford_clean['start_hour'] >= 18) & (ford_clean['start_hour'] <= 23)] = 'night'

#day of the week
ford_clean['start_weekday_num'] = ford_clean['start_time'].apply(lambda time: time.dayofweek)
day_map = {0:'Monday',1:'Tuesday',2:'Wednesday',3:'Thursday',4:'Friday',5:'Saturday',6:'Sunday'}
ford_clean['start_weekday_name'] = ford_clean['start_weekday_num'].map(day_map)

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I will be investigating distributions of individual variables.

I am going to create a user-defined functions for plotting various plots to avoid repetition

In [24]:
#user-defined function for countpot
def countplot (ford_clean, column, order = None, color = None):
    plt.figure(figsize=[9,8])
    sb.countplot(data = ford_clean, x=column, color = color, order=order);
    plt.title(f'''Distribution of {column}'''.title(), fontsize=12, weight ='bold')
    plt.xlabel(column.title(),fontsize=10, weight='bold')
    plt.ylabel('Count'.title(),fontsize=10,weight='bold')
In [25]:
#user-defined function for horizontal countplot
def countplot2(ford_clean, column, order = None, color=None):
    plt.figure(figsize=[9,8])
    sb.countplot(data = ford_clean, y=column, color = color, order=order);
    plt.title(f'''Distribution of trips based on {column}'''.title(), fontsize=12, weight ='bold')
    plt.ylabel(column.title(),fontsize=10, weight='bold')
    plt.xlabel('Trip Count'.title(),fontsize=10,weight='bold')
In [26]:
#user-defined function for histogram
def histplot(ford_clean, column, bins=None, color=None):
    plt.figure(figsize=[10,8])
    plt.hist(data = ford_clean, x=column, color=color, bins=bins);
    plt.title(f'''Distribution of {column}'''.title(), fontsize=12, weight ='bold')
    plt.xlabel(column.title(),fontsize=10, weight='bold')
    plt.ylabel('Count'.title(),fontsize=10,weight='bold')

def bivariate(ford_clean, column, order = None, color=None,hue=None):
    plt.figure(figsize=[9,8])
    sb.countplot(data = ford_clean, y=column, color = color, order=order, hue=hue);
    plt.ylabel(column.title(),fontsize=10, weight='bold')

Observation:¶

From the chart above, it can be observed that the Male gender makes use of the ford go bike services more than other genders. The count of male that make use of the services is 130651, for female it is 40844, and for other gender, which is has the least count, it is 3652. To me, this means that the male gender are more interested in the bike services than females.

Question: What time/hour of the day do people take trips or go on trips more?¶

In [44]:

Out[44]:
period_of_day
morning 67449
afternoon 67093

Observation:¶

It can be observed from the chart above that people tend to take trips in the morning or in the afternoon, rather than at night. This makes sense because it is safer to take trips during the day time that at night fall, and also for people that go to work in the morning. Also, I can also say that maybe some of the riders work at night, because the count of people that ride at night is not so little.

It also shows that they have more subscribers than regular customers, this may mean that the subscription price is more reasonable that paying for trips everytime. For instance, people would prefer paying a subscription fee of let's say 15 dollars per month, than paying 2 or 3 dollars per trip.

Observation¶

It is observed from the above chart that riders take trips more on Thursdays, followed by Tuesdays, Fridays and Wednesdays. The low count of trips on Saturdays and sundays make sense because it is weekends, and that is when people rest. During the week, people go to work or travel, or engage in one thing or the other, and then prefer to rest over the weekend. For Thursdays to be high, it is quite possible that so many people tend to have engagements that day, or there might be a discount price for trips that day

Question: What is the longest duration of trips?¶

In [33]:
bins = np.arange(0, 4000, 60)
histplot(ford_clean, 'duration_sec', bins=bins, color = 'green')

Observation¶

It can be seen that the duration of most trips takes about 500 seconds to about 650 seconds. This is approximately 8 - 10 minutes. It is also seen that the count of the duration of trips that take about 3500 to 4000 seconds (approx. 58-66 minutes) is very low. From these observations, I came to the conclusion that people prefer taking bikes to locations that are not so far, that is a trip that will just take them about 10 minutes or less than 20 minutes, than taking bikes to farther locations which would be about an hour or more.

Observation¶

From the plots above, most stations begin and end at Market St at 10th St and San Francisco Caltrain station2. This may mean that people prefer using these routes for their trips, probably because their start and final destinations are closer to these stations. It is just an assumption. There might be other factors involved that make these stations have the highest number of trips (start and end). This may be looked into.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Yes, I performed some transformations on the Age column that was added. The hist plot for Age was skewed to the right, as there were ages that were over 100. I decided to remove those Ages that were greater than age 100 and also ages that were equal to 0 which were null values. I had to perform these transformations to have a clearer view of the age distribution, and for it to be somewhat evenly distributed because there were no much riders who were older than 100 also.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Yes I performed some operations to tidy the data. Firstly, I converted the datatypes of the start_time and end_time variables to datetime datatype, the member_birth_year variable from float to int, because years cannot be in float (1999.0), the member_gender and bike_rides to categorical variables. After that, I split the start_time into hour, day, and month to give be able to get better insight from the data, and I also used the member_birth_year to get the ages of the members. Because there were null values in the Age column which was hindering me from making a plot, I decided to fill the null values with 0, and later dropped the values. I did all these operations to give me a much better insight on the dataset.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

I observed the relationships of user type based on number of trips in the top 10 stations. I saw that subscribers have more trips in the stations than customers. This made me conclude that customers may be tourists. I also checked the count of trips in the top 10 stations based on hour of the day and day of the week and saw that most trips occur in the mornings in some stations and also most trips occur during weekdays. Male gender also seem to take more trips in all the stations than the female gender

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

I observed the duration of trips in the top 10 stations. I saw that the highest duration of trip takes about 14 minutes in one station and the least duration of trip in another station takes about 10 minutes

Observation¶

In some stations, trips are longer in the afternoon and at night than in the morning. In the second plot, it is seen that trips are longer during the weekends in some stations.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

I observed that most customers trips are during the weekends, which is not really surprising. It might just imply that most customers are tourists. I also observed that there was no much difference between the male and female gender that take trips during the day and week

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

I was quite surprised that most stations trips are longer in the afternoon and at night. It may mean that passengers tend to go to farther locations at the times of the day or the bikes tend to drive slower, especially at night, to ensure a safe trip.

Conclusions¶

In this data visualization analysis, I carried out exploratory data analysis by investigating a dataset called Ford GoBike share 2019. I carried out some cleaning and tidying in the data, like incorrect datatypes and adding additional columns to help with more insight. I also investigated the relationships between several variables in the datatset. I performed Univariate explorations, Bivariate explorations and Multivariate explorations. I observed in the dataset that there were riders above the age of 100, and also that most riders were males. I also observed that most stations had more subscribers than customers, and that the duration of most stations trips were in the afternoon and at night.

This analysis unveiled several relationships between variables and gave so much insight into the dataset
